@node "Einleitung" "Introduction"
When a program saves anything, in many cases an icon will be saved too.
This icon, which is from type "project", contains an entry named "default
tool", which contains the name (and if necessary also the path) of the
program, which have saved the file. When you make a double-click to this
icon, the Amiga first starts the program stored in the default tool, and
after this, this program loads the clicked file.

The problem, which can now arise, is the following:
When you for example get some pictures or samples from an Amiga-CD-Rom,
and you copy these with their icons to your harddisk, then you can in
many cases not open it with a double-click, because in their default tool
there is a program which isn't available or is stored in another path.

The same problem exists, when you change the directory structure, and the
program (here for example MuchMore) swaps the place from "dh0:Util/MuchMore"
to "dh0:Applications/Tools/MuchMore".

In all these cases you normally have to change the default tool of your
icons manually. But now, with "Deftool-Manager", you can read in all
existing default tools with a mouse click, and after this you can define,
whether and how these should be replaced. Then you can replace all default
tools of your icons automatically. These assign-lists can be saved for a
later use in other directories. Also a log-file can be created, to store
all actions which will be done, for later reading.
@endnode

@node "benoetigt" "What will be needed to run the program"
To start Deftool-Manager on your computer, you need the following things:

  - An Amiga ;-)
  - Amiga-OS 3.0 or higher


Machines used for testings:

  - Amiga 1200 with OS3.1, Blizzard 1230-IV  68030 board with 50 MHz,
    68882-FPU 50 MHz, 32 MB Fastmem, 2 MB Chipmem.

  - Amiga 1200 with OS3.0, 2 MB Chipmem.

  - Amiga 4000 with OS3.1, 68030 with 25 MHz, 20 MB Fastmem, 2MB Chipmem.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
The installation is very easy. Simply drag the icon of Deftool-Manager to
the place you want to store it. There will be no additional files needed,
and the used libraries should all be there, because they belong to OS3.0.

The documentation you are reading now should be copied to this path too,
but this is optional, because it has no influence to the program itself.
@endnode

@node "Benutzung" "How to use it"
After the start of the program you will see a window with the following
gadgets:

At the top right you can type in the path, which will be scanned / replaced.
You can either type it in or use the gadget to the right, which opens a
filerequester. Below this you can define the path and name of the log-file,
either by typing it in or using the filerequester-gadget at the right of it.
With the "Open"-gadget the log-file will be opened, and all following
actions will be written to it. With the "Close"-gadget the file will be
closed. It can later be inspected with a text viewer.

The gadget "Scan directory" reads in all default tools in the given directory.
The entries found will be presented in the list "Source". When you click to
an entry there, the corresponding entry of the list "Destination" will be
shown in the string gadget at the bottom of the window. Here you can edit
the default tool (which is empty at the beginning). In the list "Destination"
you will see the default tools, which will replace the default tools in the
"Source"-list.
After you have typed in an replacement for the original default tool, this
new one will be shown in the right list. When you DON'T WANT a replacement
to a default tool shown in the "Source"-list, you sinply can leave the
corresponding entry in the "Destination"-list empty.
The first entry in the left (Source-)list will be replaced with the one,
which is stored in the first entry of the right (Destination-)list, the
second at the left will be replaced with the second on the right, and so on.

With the gadget "Change default tools" all default tools in the given
directory will be replaced with the corresponding parts of the "Destination"-
list. Possibly appearing errors will be announced by the program, and also
written to the log-file (if the log-file was activated).


@{U}There are also some menu commands, you can use:@{UU}

@{B}About@{UB}

Shows you informations about the program and the author.

@{B}Save definitions@{UB}

Saves the assigns of the source- and destination list in a file. This file
is pure ASCII-text, which can be edited with any editor. The assignment is
very easy. Here an example:

	dh0:programs/DPaint5=dh2:Progs/DP5
	ShowMePicture=MultiView

These example file contains two assignments. The first was at original at
"dh0:programs/DPaint5", which will be replaced by "dh2:Progs/DP5", and the
second one was "ShowMePicture", which will be replaced by "MultiView".

@{B}Load definitions@{UB}

Loads the files you saved with "Save definitions". After this, the two
lists will be filled with the new contents. Please note, that after the
reading of a file it could be possible, that the given path have to be new
defined, because perhaps no matching project icons are available in the
current path.

@{B}Quit@{UB}

With this command you can exit the program. A possible open log-file will
be close before automatically. You can also exit the program with a click
to the close gadget of the window (at top left side).
@endnode

